---
title: Constraints
description: Constraints declare what must be true in your system. When conditions aren't met, they raise requirements for resolvers to handle.
---

Constraints are the heart of Directive - they declare what must be true, and let the runtime handle when and how. {% .lead %}

---

## Basic Constraints

Define constraints in your module:

```typescript
const userModule = createModule("user", {
  schema: {
    facts: {
      userId: t.number(),
      user: t.object<User>().nullable(),
      loading: t.boolean(),
    },
    requirements: {
      FETCH_USER: t.object<{ userId: number }>(),
    },
  },

  constraints: {
    needsUser: {
      when: (facts) => facts.userId > 0 && !facts.user && !facts.loading,
      require: { type: "FETCH_USER", userId: (facts) => facts.userId },
    },
  },
});
```

---

## Anatomy of a Constraint

```typescript
constraints: {
  constraintName: {
    // When is this constraint violated?
    when: (facts, derive) => boolean,

    // What requirement does it raise?
    require: {
      type: "REQUIREMENT_TYPE",
      // Additional payload (optional)
      data: (facts) => facts.someValue,
    },

    // Optional: priority for conflict resolution
    priority: 100,

    // Optional: run after these constraints
    after: ["otherConstraint"],
  },
}
```

---

## The `when` Function

The `when` function returns `true` when the constraint is violated:

```typescript
constraints: {
  // Fires when user is needed but not loaded
  needsUser: {
    when: (facts) => facts.userId > 0 && !facts.user,
    require: { type: "FETCH_USER" },
  },

  // Fires when session is expired
  sessionExpired: {
    when: (facts) => facts.session && facts.session.expiresAt < Date.now(),
    require: { type: "REFRESH_SESSION" },
  },
}
```

### Using Derivations

Access derivations in your conditions:

```typescript
constraints: {
  needsAuth: {
    when: (facts, derive) => !derive.isAuthenticated && facts.requiresAuth,
    require: { type: "REDIRECT_TO_LOGIN" },
  },
}
```

---

## Dynamic Requirements

Pass data from facts to requirements:

```typescript
constraints: {
  fetchUser: {
    when: (facts) => facts.userId > 0 && !facts.user,
    require: {
      type: "FETCH_USER",
      userId: (facts) => facts.userId,
      options: (facts) => ({ includeProfile: facts.needsProfile }),
    },
  },
}
```

The resolver receives this data:

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchUser: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // req = { type: "FETCH_USER", userId: 123, options: { includeProfile: true } }
      const user = await api.getUser(req.userId, req.options);
      ctx.facts.user = user;
    },
  },
}
```

---

## Priority

Use priority to control which constraints are evaluated first:

```typescript
constraints: {
  // Higher priority runs first (default: 0)
  emergency: {
    priority: 1000,
    when: (facts) => facts.criticalError,
    require: { type: "EMERGENCY_SHUTDOWN" },
  },

  normal: {
    priority: 50,
    when: (facts) => facts.needsRefresh,
    require: { type: "REFRESH_DATA" },
  },

  low: {
    priority: -100,
    when: (facts) => facts.shouldPrefetch,
    require: { type: "PREFETCH_NEXT" },
  },
}
```

{% callout title="Priority order" %}
Higher numbers run first. Same priority constraints run in definition order.
{% /callout %}

---

## Ordering with `after`

Explicitly order constraints:

```typescript
constraints: {
  validateUser: {
    when: (facts) => !facts.userValidated,
    require: { type: "VALIDATE_USER" },
  },

  fetchProfile: {
    // Only evaluates after validateUser is satisfied
    after: ["validateUser"],
    when: (facts) => facts.userValidated && !facts.profile,
    require: { type: "FETCH_PROFILE" },
  },
}
```

---

## Async Constraints

Constraints can be async for complex conditions:

```typescript
constraints: {
  needsPermission: {
    when: async (facts, derive) => {
      // Async check (use sparingly - blocks reconciliation)
      const hasPermission = await checkPermission(facts.userId, "read");
      return !hasPermission;
    },
    require: { type: "REQUEST_PERMISSION" },
    timeout: 5000, // Timeout for async check
  },
}
```

{% callout type="warning" title="Async constraints" %}
Async constraints block the reconciliation loop. Use them only when necessary, and set reasonable timeouts.
{% /callout %}

---

## Constraint Lifecycle

1. **Fact changes** trigger reconciliation
2. **Constraints evaluate** in priority/order
3. **Violated constraints** raise requirements
4. **Resolvers handle** requirements
5. **Loop repeats** until all constraints satisfied

```
facts change, constraints check, requirements raised, resolvers run, repeat
```

---

## Multiple Requirements

A constraint can only raise one requirement. Use multiple constraints for multiple requirements:

```typescript
constraints: {
  needsUser: {
    when: (facts) => !facts.user,
    require: { type: "FETCH_USER" },
  },
  needsPreferences: {
    when: (facts) => !facts.preferences,
    require: { type: "FETCH_PREFERENCES" },
  },
}
```

Both requirements can be resolved in parallel.

---

## Disabling Constraints

Constraints can be conditionally disabled:

```typescript
constraints: {
  autoSave: {
    enabled: (facts) => facts.settings.autoSaveEnabled,
    when: (facts) => facts.hasUnsavedChanges,
    require: { type: "SAVE_DOCUMENT" },
  },
}
```

---

## Best Practices

### Keep Conditions Simple

```typescript
// Good - simple, readable
when: (facts) => facts.userId > 0 && !facts.user

// Less ideal - complex logic
when: (facts) => {
  const needsData = facts.userId > 0;
  const notLoaded = !facts.user;
  const notLoading = !facts.loading;
  const hasPermission = facts.permissions.includes("read");
  return needsData && notLoaded && notLoading && hasPermission;
}
```

### Use Derivations for Complex Logic

```typescript
derive: {
  shouldFetchUser: (facts) =>
    facts.userId > 0 &&
    !facts.user &&
    !facts.loading &&
    facts.permissions.includes("read"),
},

constraints: {
  fetchUser: {
    when: (facts, derive) => derive.shouldFetchUser,
    require: { type: "FETCH_USER" },
  },
}
```

### Avoid Side Effects

```typescript
// Bad - side effects in when
when: (facts) => {
  console.log("Checking constraint"); // No!
  analytics.track("constraint_check"); // No!
  return facts.needsData;
}

// Good - pure function
when: (facts) => facts.needsData
```

---

## Debugging Constraints

Enable logging to see constraint evaluation:

```typescript
import { loggingPlugin } from 'directive/plugins';

const system = createSystem({
  module: userModule,
  plugins: [loggingPlugin({ constraints: true })],
});
```

